        'title' => 'Ethics Policies',
        'content' => '<p><strong><em>Cuadernos de Administración</em></strong> is a biannual publication of the Universidad del Valle, a higher education state institution; it does not have any kind of economic or political commitments with any academic or business organization. The magazine is subject to the ethical guidelines of the Committee on Publications Ethics (COPE) and the Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association (APA-6th edition) (APA, 2011).</p><p>Ethical responsibilities of the General Editor</p><p>The General Editor is responsible for the editorial process of the journal; he/she oversees compliance with the internal rules of the magazine and for the integrity, efficiency and transparency of the editorial process. The following ethical responsibilities have to do with this role:</p><p>A. Communication with authors: he/she is responsible for giving information about the editorial process of each manuscript, whenever the authors request information about it.</p><p>B. Decision-making: the General Editor should guide his/her decisions based on criteria of justice, fairness. Economic, commercial and/or personal interests should not prevail over the transparency of the editorial process.</p><p>C. Confidentiality: Communications between Editor-authors and Editor-reviewers are confidential; the magazine uses a blind peer review process; therefore, the identity of authors and reviewers should remain anonymous to avoid any conflict of interest or bias in the assessment issued by the arbitrators. The General Editor should not share any information related with the manuscript or the process to third parties or colleagues unrelated to the journal, except in those cases where the concept of an expert is needed, and for which the express permission of the authors is requested. The General Editor should not use the results of scientific research of unpublished manuscripts for his/her own benefit or that of others, except with the express permission of the authors.</p><p>D. Reply to criticisms and concerns: The General Editor is obliged to respond to the concerns and suggestions of the authors and reviewers regarding the contents published by the magazine, assuring disclosure of dissertations that contribute significantly to the fields of study in the journal using the figure of "Letters to the Editor"</p><p><strong>Ethical responsibilities of reviewers</strong></p><p>They are responsible for the academic assessment of the manuscripts, they must maintain a position of impartiality and confidentiality; their commitments include:</p><p>A. Confidentiality: reviewers should not share any information related to the manuscript or the process being evaluated to third parties. If an external opinion is required, they must request explicit authorization to the General Editor, and the reasons to make the request. Likewise, reviewers should not use the content of unpublished manuscripts for personal gain or that of others. If an author, editor or reader suspects of appropriation of ideas or data of an author by an evaluator, they must act according to the guidelines of COPE in relation to the appropriation of ideas and data.</p><p>B. Assessment Capacity: upon receiving a request for arbitration, reviewers should respond within seven (7) days about whether they are willing to make the process; if their answer is yes, they are on duty to respond critically and friendly to requests for information from the General Editor and the authors. If the reviewer manifest conflict of interest with the author(s) and/or the research, they must do so in writing to the General Editor, who decides whether to accept or reject their participation in the evaluation process.</p><p>C. Error detection and bad editorial practices: if in the review process, possible malpractices by the authors are evident, the referees are obliged to give notice to the General Editor, who proceeds according to the COPE guidelines for care of bad editorial practices, as appropriate.</p><p><strong>Ethical responsibilities of the authors</strong></p><p>The ethical conduct of the authors should be guided by knowledge and respect for intellectual property rights, as well as transparency and integrity of the data presented in the research results. The authors must respond ethically to:</p><p>A. Honest and transparent data presentation and analysis: The authors are obliged to present in a clearly and accurately way the origin and methods of data collection in their research; in the same way, they must detail the process whenever the General Editor or the reviewers demand it. The refusal of the authors to such requests is considered a dubious attitude, by which the magazine adheres to the procedures established by the COPE regarding "questionable data".</p><p>B1. Confidentiality of the research participants: both the authors and the magazine <strong><em>Cuadernos de Administración</em></strong> are obliged to protect the confidentiality of the research participants. The authors should not provide any information enabling the identification and location of the research subjects; in addition, it cannot be published any data concerning persons or entities related to the participants, such as family, clients or organizations. The authors should ensure the publication of personal content of the participants through an informed consent, and submit these documents (if necessary) to the General Editor and referees.</p><p>C. Sponsorship and conflicts of interest: the authors are obliged to declare the entities or persons who have funded the research project from which comes the manuscript to be published; in the same way, they must declare potential conflicts of interest they may have with both the publishing entity as well as those subject to the investigation. The American Psychological Association (APA) (2011) believes that an author has conflicts of interest when:</p><p>C1. They are engaged in the organizational structure of certain organization and the publication of the manuscript can benefit that organization. This relationship is justified by the existence of a salary, consulting fees, or owning shares of the company; in the same way, to belong to any Board or any other decision-making body.</p><p>C2. There are family or personal relationships with organizations or individuals who are subject of the research.</p><p>If there is suspicion of undeclared conflict of interest, the magazine acts according to COPE’s guidelines regarding "Conflict of Interest".</p><p>D. Authorship and acknowledgments: APA (2011) defines the authors as follows:</p><p>Those who make substantial scientific contributions to the study. These may include formulating the problem or hypothesis, structuring the experimental design, organizing and conducting the statistical analysis, interpreting the results, or writing most of the document (p. 18).</p><p>In addition, authorship also means "taking responsibility for the published content" (Tur-Viñes, Fonseca-Mora, and Gutierrez-San-Miguel, 2012). Smaller contributions in support work must be published in a note of the authors as "Acknowledgments" to those persons or entities who have participated in activities supporting the main research process. Disputes over authorship (if exist) should be resolved among research participants and the manuscript publishing process will be frozen until these discrepancies be resolved. The authors, under the direction of the magazine, should resolve authoring disagreements as stated in the COPE guidelines, in "Changes in Authorship," as appropriate.</p><p>F. Error Detection: The authors are obliged to inform the General Editor of errors detected in the manuscript, ulterior to the publication, and request corrections by <strong><em>Cuadernos de Administración</em></strong>.</p><p>G. Arbitration Process: by submitting a manuscript to the editing process by <strong><em>Cuadernos de Administración</em></strong>, the authors are obliged to answer carefully and quickly the suggestions made by the referees (the response times are stipulated in the Guidelines Authors); the delay or obliteration in the response is synonymous with disinterest for the editorial process, and it will cause the removal of the manuscript.</p><p><strong>Bad editorial practices</strong></p><p>In addition to that which regulates the publication ethics of <strong><em>Cuadernos de Administración,</em></strong> it should also be noted those practices considered undesirable in the publishing process:</p><p><strong>Editors and referees</strong></p><p>Any violation of the confidentiality agreement established between the editor /author / referees will be considered a bad editorial practice. Likewise, the fraudulent use of unpublished material (plagiarism) by the General Editor and reviewers is considered unethical, and it could be penalized by the Intellectual Property and Copyright Law. Finally, any other exploitation of material posted by any member of the Editorial or Scientific Committees; group of arbitrators, or by the publisher, is considered as a bad practice.</p><p><strong>Authors</strong></p><p>Reply: it is considered bad practice to submit a manuscript for publication in two journals and other means of disclosure, or in another language. The authors must comply with the exclusivity agreement which requires the journal as document, before starting the publishing process.</p><p>Previously published work: to submit a document to apply in <strong><em>Cuadernos de Administración</em></strong> that has already been published in any other media (physical or electronic) is considered unacceptable; the authors must comply with the exclusivity agreement required by the magazine, where they specifically state that the presented document has never been published in any other media. If a case of "redundant Publication" is detected, the magazine will proceed according to COPE’s guidelines.</p><p>Manuscripts posted by parts: <strong><em>Cuadernos de Administración</em></strong> invites authors to submit manuscripts that are full and meaningful for the advancement of research fields; "split" publication (Piecemeal publication) is considered bad practice: when several manuscripts of the same research project are presented. APA (2011) mentions a number of exceptions for these types of "split" publications, which are those manuscripts resulting from multidisciplinary research, long-range or longitudinal projects; in these cases, it is permitted the publication of several manuscripts resulting from a single research, as the presentation of the results is in the interest of various audiences, and it warrants publication in different media. If this case occurs, the authors must give notice to the General Editor.</p>Plagiarism and self-plagiarism: it is considered bad practice, besides being penalized by the Law on Copyright and Intellectual Property, to present as own research results than are not; the authors are obliged to cite the previous work that is necessary for the construction of their manuscript. Likewise, they should cite their own previous work following the same rules as with other authors; self-plagiarism is a bad practice that stems from the replica, as the citation identifies the new contributions made by the authors. <strong><em>Cuadernos de Administración</em></strong> uses the anti-plagiarism "<strong><em>Turnitin</em></strong>" tool, and it adheres to the guidelines of COPE in relation to "Plagiarism".',
