  'layoutInstructions' => 
  array (
    'en_US' => '<p>Layout instructions</p><h4>To add links to the layout process</h4><p>When transferring a submission to HTML or PDF, make sure the hyperlinks are active.</p><h4>A. If the author provides a link to the reference</h4><ol><li>Starting from the document in a text processor (e.g., Word), add the phrase SEE ELEMENT at the end of the reference with an internet address.</li><li>Convert the phrase into a hyperlink by selecting it and using the tool "Insert Hyperlink" (for Word).</li></ol><h4>B. Search by References in Google Scholar</h4><ol><li>Starting from the document in a text processor (e.g., Word), copy the title of the referenced work, or the author and title).</li><li>Paste the title selected between %22s, writing a + between each word: http://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22COPY+TITLE+HERE%22&amp;hl=en&amp;lr=&amp;btnG=Search</li><li>Add the phrase SEARCH IN GS at the end of the reference in the article.</li><li>Convert the phrase into a hyperlink (in Word: select the text and g oto Insert Hyperlink).</li></ol><h4>C. Activating the search by references with a DOI for readers</h4><ol><li>If the document submitted is still in Word, copy a reference lot in CrossRef Text Query http://www.crossref.org/freeTextQuery/</li><li>Paste each DOI provided by the search in the following URL (between = and &amp;): http://www.cmaj.ca/cgi/external_ref?access_num=PASTE DOI#HERE&amp;link_type=DOI</li><li>Add the phrase CrossRef at the end of each citation on the list of references of the document submitted.</li></ol>Convert that phrase into a hyperlink by selecting the phrase and using the Word function of Insert hyperlink and the corresponding URL prepared in #2.',
  ),
